
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `false` yek dastoor sade ast ke be maenay "na dorost" ya "ghalat" ast. Vaghti `false` ejra mishe, yek code error (1) barmigardanad, yani dastoor ba movafaghiat anjam nashode.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `false` --> Hich gozine-i nadarad. Fagat khodash ejra mishe va ghalat barmigardanad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ false
    $ echo $?
    1
    🔹 Dastoor `false` ejra mishe va ba `echo $?` code error (1) namayesh dade mishe.

    $ if false; then echo "dorost"; else echo "ghalat"; fi
    ghalat
    🔹 Dar yek dastoor `if`, `false` baes mishe ghesmat `else` ejra beshe.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ false; echo "dastoor ejra shod"
    dastoor ejra shod
    🔹 Agarche `false` ghalat barmigardanad, vali dastoor badi ham ejra mishe.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `false` command is a simple command that represents "not true" or "false". When `false` is executed, it returns an error code (1), indicating the command did not succeed.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `false` --> It has no options. It simply executes and returns false.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ false
    $ echo $?
    1
    🔹 The `false` command is executed and `echo $?` displays the error code (1).

    $ if false; then echo "true"; else echo "false"; fi
    false
    🔹 In an `if` statement, `false` causes the `else` part to be executed.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ false; echo "command executed"
    command executed
    🔹 Even though `false` returns false, the next command still executes.

